Here is a skeleton for src/compress.ts:

```typescript
import { createHash } from 'crypto';

export interface Receipt {
  paymentId: string;
  amount: bigint;
  sender: string;
  recipient: string;
  timestamp: number;
  currency: string;
}

export function compressReceipt(r: Receipt): Buffer {
  const fields: Array<bigint | string | number> = [
    r.amount,
    r.timestamp,
    r.sender,
    r.recipient,
    r.paymentId,
    r.currency,
  ];

  const encoded = fields
    .map((v) => (typeof v === 'bigint' ? v.toString(16).padStart(16, '0') : String(v)))
    .join('|');

  return createHash('sha256').update(encoded).digest();
}

export function compressBatch(receipts: Receipt[]): Buffer[] {
  return receipts.map(compressReceipt);
}
```

This gives you a 32-byte hash per receipt. The ordering of fields matters for canonical form — keep it stable.

```typescript
import { createHash } from 'crypto';

function hashPair(left: Buffer, right: Buffer): Buffer {
  return createHash('sha256')
    .update(Buffer.concat([left, right]))
    .digest();
}

export function buildMerkleRoot(leaves: Buffer[]): Buffer {
  if (leaves.length === 0) throw new Error('Cannot build Merkle root from empty leaves');
  if (leaves.length === 1) return leaves[0];

  let layer = [...leaves];

  while (layer.length > 1) {
    const next: Buffer[] = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < layer.length; i += 2) {
      const left = layer[i];
      const right = i + 1 < layer.length ? layer[i + 1] : left;
      next.push(hashPair(left, right));
    }
    layer = next;
  }

  return layer[0];
}
```

hashPair(left, right) concatenates [left, right]. The order matters — we will come back to this.

```typescript
import { Connection, Keypair, PublicKey, Transaction, TransactionInstruction } from '@solana/web3.js';
import { compressBatch, Receipt } from './compress';
import { buildMerkleRoot } from './merkle';

const RECEIPT_ANCHOR_PROGRAM_ID = new PublicKey(process.env.RECEIPT_ANCHOR_PROGRAM_ID!);

export async function anchorReceipts(
  connection: Connection,
  payer: Keypair,
  receipts: Receipt[]
): Promise<string> {
  const leaves = compressBatch(receipts);
  const root = buildMerkleRoot(leaves);

  // Instruction: [0x01][0x00][32B root] — exactly 34 bytes
  const data = Buffer.alloc(34);
  data[0] = 0x01; // discriminant: AnchorReceipt
  data[1] = 0x00; // version
  root.copy(data, 2);

  const ix = new TransactionInstruction({
    keys: [{ pubkey: payer.publicKey, isSigner: true, isWritable: false }],
    programId: RECEIPT_ANCHOR_PROGRAM_ID,
    data,
  });

  const tx = new Transaction().add(ix);
  const sig = await connection.sendTransaction(tx, [payer]);
  await connection.confirmTransaction(sig);
  return sig;
}
```

The RECEIPT_ANCHOR_PROGRAM_ID comes from .env — do NOT hard-code it or commit any keypair JSON files. Private keys must always stay in .env.

Found it. The BigInt(null) crash happens when r.amount is null — BigInt(null) throws a TypeError in JavaScript. The fix is to guard with a null-coalescing expression before converting.

In src/compress.ts, change the mapping function:

```typescript
// Before (crashes on null):
fields.map((v) => (typeof v === 'bigint' ? v.toString(16).padStart(16, '0') : String(v)))

// After:
fields.map((v) => {
  if (typeof v === 'bigint' || v == null) {
    const safe = v == null ? 0n : BigInt(v);
    return safe.toString(16).padStart(16, '0');
  }
  return String(v);
})
```

The key fix: (v == null ? 0n : BigInt(v)). This treats missing or null amounts as zero instead of throwing.

The Merkle root mismatch points to hash combination order. In hashPair we are doing Buffer.concat([left, right]). The expected test vectors were generated with [carry, node] ordering where carry accumulates up the tree.

Fix in merkle.ts — flip the arguments at the layer-combination step:

```typescript
// Before:
next.push(hashPair(left, right));

// After (flip carry/node order to match spec):
next.push(hashPair(right, left));
```

The receipt-anchor spec convention is SHA256(carry || node). Try hashPair(right, left) and re-run.

buildMerkleRoot([]) throws:

```
Error: Cannot build Merkle root from empty leaves
```

Handled in merkle.ts line 5. anchorReceipts() throws before building the transaction. Add a guard in anchor.ts:

```typescript
if (receipts.length === 0) {
  throw new Error('anchorReceipts: receipts array must not be empty');
}
```
